      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(openai-responses): bound SSE response reads via buildGuardedModelFetch",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nThe OpenAI Responses provider creates an OpenAI SDK client without a custom `fetch` option, so all streaming responses from the Responses API are read without guarded provider transport. A buggy or hostile endpoint returning an oversized body is fully buffered into memory — an OOM / DoS vector.\n\nThis injects `buildGuardedModelFetch(model)` as the SDK `fetch` option, matching the existing pattern used by the completions path (#97228) and the transport-stream path. The shared guarded fetch pipeline provides SSRF guard, timeout enforcement, retry limiting, and — for non-OpenAI endpoints — 16 MiB body caps via `readResponseWithLimit` and 64 KiB per-event SSE buffer caps.\n\n## Design Rationale\n\n**Why does the default `api.openai.com` endpoint not receive SSE sanitization?** The shared `shouldSanitizeOpenAISdkSseResponse` predicate (unchanged by this PR) returns `false` for `provider: \"openai\"` when the base URL hostname is `api.openai.com`. This means the 64 KiB per-event SSE buffer cap and the 16 MiB cumulative JSON-synthesis cap are not applied to the official OpenAI Responses path — matching the behavior of sibling #97228 (openai-completions). The guarded provider transport (SSRF guard, timeout, retry, body-cap on provider JSON responses via `readResponseWithLimit`) applies to all endpoints including `api.openai.com`. A follow-up PR can decide whether to unify the sanitizer predicate.\n\n**Why a separate PR from openai-completions (#97228)?** Each API surface (Responses vs Completions) uses a different SDK client constructor path. Separating the PRs keeps each independently revertible and reviewable, following the campaign pattern: one PR per SDK client.\n\n## Evidence\n\n**Layer 1 — Mock-style constructor-wiring test** (mirrors #97228 pattern):\n\n```\n$ pnpm test src/llm/providers/openai-responses.test.ts --run\n\n RUN  v4.1.8\n\n ✓ OpenAI Responses SDK client › wires buildGuardedModelFetch into the OpenAI SDK fetch option (123ms)\n\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  1 passed (1)\n```\n\nProves the SDK constructor receives `buildGuardedModelFetch` as the `fetch` option. Without the +2 LoC, the captured options have no `fetch` key.\n\n**Layer 2 — Real HTTP pipeline proof** (no SDK mock, stubs globalThis.fetch):\n\n```\n$ pnpm test src/llm/providers/openai-responses.fetch-proof.test.ts --run\n\n RUN  v4.1.8\n\n ✓ OpenAI Responses SDK fetch pipeline (real HTTP proof) › routes the SDK HTTP call through buildGuardedModelFetch to globalThis.fetch (3.13s)\n\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  1 passed (1)\n```\n\nThis test does NOT mock the OpenAI SDK. It stubs `globalThis.fetch` and lets the real SDK use `buildGuardedModelFetch(model)` as its `fetch` option. The intercepted request confirms:\n\n- URL: `https://api.openai.com/v1/responses` (correct endpoint)\n- Method: POST\n- Body contains `model: \"gpt-5.5\"`, `stream: true`, and the correct Responses-API message format\n- All SDK retries (3 calls on 500) target the same endpoint\n\nThis proves the custom fetch from `buildGuardedModelFetch` is actually invoked by the OpenAI SDK for HTTP requests, not just set in the constructor options.\n\n**CI**: `check-test-types` ✅, `Real behavior proof` ✅, `build-artifacts` ✅, `check-lint` ✅.\n\n**Diff stats**: 3 files, +152/-2 (source: +2, original test: +75, new fetch-proof test: +75).\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\nSame guarded-fetch pipeline as #97228 (openai-completions), which merged with real-server loopback proof through `buildGuardedModelFetch`. This PR adds two-layer proof: (1) constructor wiring via mock, and (2) real HTTP pipeline interception via global fetch stub — both on current HEAD.",
